[src:arangodb/graph-database] A **graph database** (**GDB**) is a database that uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges, and properties to represent and store data.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] A key concept of the system is the graph (or edge or relationship).
[src:arangodb/graph-database] The graph relates the data items in the store to a collection of nodes and edges, the edges representing the relationships between the nodes.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] The relationships allow data in the store to be linked together directly and, in many cases, retrieved with one operation.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Graph databases hold the relationships between data as a priority.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Querying relationships is fast because they are perpetually stored in the database.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Relationships can be intuitively visualized using graph databases, making them useful for heavily inter-connected data.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Graph databases are commonly referred to as a NoSQL database.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Graph databases are similar to 1970s network model databases in that both represent general graphs, but network-model databases operate at a lower level of abstraction and lack easy traversal over a chain of edges.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] The underlying storage mechanism of graph databases can vary.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Relationships are first-class citizens in a graph database and can be labeled, directed, and given properties.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and store the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes a level of abstraction between the graph database management system and physical storage devices).
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Others use a key–value store or document-oriented database for storage, making them inherently NoSQL structures.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] As of 2021, no graph query language has been universally adopted in the same way as SQL was for relational databases.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] There is a wide variety of systems used, many of which are tightly tied to one product.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Early standardization efforts led to multi-vendor query languages like Gremlin, SPARQL, and Cypher.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In September 2019 a proposal for a project to create a new standard graph query language (ISO/IEC 39075 Information Technology — Database Languages — GQL) was approved by members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1(ISO/IEC JTC 1).
[src:arangodb/graph-database] GQL is intended to be a declarative database query language, like SQL.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In addition to having query language interfaces, some graph databases are accessed through application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Graph databases differ from graph compute engines.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Graph databases are technologies that are translations of the relational online transaction processing (OLTP) databases.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] On the other hand, graph compute engines are used in online analytical processing (OLAP) for bulk analysis.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Graph databases attracted considerable attention in the 2000s, due to the successes of major technology corporations using proprietary graph databases, along with the introduction of open-source graph databases.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] One study concluded that an RDBMS was "comparable" in performance to existing graph analysis engines at executing graph queries.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In the mid-1960s, navigational databases such as IBM's IMS supported tree-like structures in its hierarchical model, but the strict tree structure could be circumvented with virtual records.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Graph structures could be represented in network model databases from the late 1960s.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] CODASYL, which had defined COBOL in 1959, defined the Network Database Language in 1969.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Labeled graphs could be represented in graph databases from the mid-1980s, such as the Logical Data Model.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Commercial object databases (ODBMSs) emerged in the early 1990s.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In 2000, the Object Data Management Group published a standard language for defining object and relationship (graph) structures in their ODMG'93 publication.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In the mid-to-late 2000s, commercial graph databases with ACID guarantees such as Neo4j and Oracle Spatial and Graph became available.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In the 2010s, commercial ACID graph databases that could be scaled horizontally became available.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Further, SAP HANA brought in-memory and columnar technologies to graph databases.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Also in the 2010s, multi-model databases that supported graph models (and other models such as relational database or document-oriented database) became available, such as OrientDB, ArangoDB, and MarkLogic (starting with its 7.0 version).
[src:arangodb/graph-database] During this time, graph databases of various types have become especially popular with social network analysis with the advent of social media companies.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Also during the decade, cloud-based graph databases such as Amazon Neptune and Neo4j AuraDB became available.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Based on graph theory, graph databases store data in a way that reflects how it is conceptually understood, using nodes to represent entities and edges to represent the relationships between them.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] It consists of a set of objects, such as a node or an edge.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] A labeled-property graph model is represented by a set of nodes, relationships, properties, and labels.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Both nodes of data and their relationships are named and can store properties represented by key–value pairs.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] The edges representing the relationships have two qualities: they always have a start node and an end node, and are directed; making the graph a directed graph.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] This is useful in providing additional metadata and semantics to relationships of the nodes.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Direct storage of relationships allows a constant-time traversal.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In an RDF graph model, each addition of information is represented with a separate node.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] For example, imagine a scenario where a user has to add a name property for a person represented as a distinct node in the graph.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In a labeled-property graph model, this would be done with an addition of a name property into the node of the person.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] However, in an RDF, the user has to add a separate node called `hasName` connecting it to the original person node.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Specifically, an RDF graph model is composed of nodes and arcs.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] An RDF graph notation or a statement is represented by: a node for the subject, a node for the object, and an arc for the predicate.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] A node may be left blank, a literal and/or be identified by a URI.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] A literal for a node may be of two types: plain (untyped) and typed.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] A plain literal has a lexical form and optionally a language tag.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] A typed literal is made up of a string with a URI that identifies a particular datatype.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] A blank node may be used to accurately illustrate the state of the data when the data does not have a URI.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Graph databases are a powerful tool for graph-like queries.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] For example, computing the shortest path between two nodes in the graph.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Other graph-like queries can be performed over a graph database in a natural way (for example graph's diameter computations or community detection).
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Graphs are flexible, meaning it allows the user to insert new data into the existing graph without loss of application functionality.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] There is no need for the designer of the database to plan out extensive details of the database's future use cases.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and "store" the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes another level of abstraction between the graph database, the graph database management system and the physical devices where the data is actually stored).
[src:arangodb/graph-database] A node would be represented as any other document store, but edges that link two different nodes hold special attributes inside its document; a _from and _to attributes.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Data lookup performance is dependent on the access speed from one particular node to another.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Because index-free adjacency enforces the nodes to have direct physical RAM addresses and physically point to other adjacent nodes, it results in a fast retrieval.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] A native graph system with index-free adjacency does not have to move through any other type of data structures to find links between the nodes.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Directly related nodes in a graph are stored in the cache once one of the nodes are retrieved, making the data lookup even faster than the first time a user fetches a node.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] However, such advantage comes at a cost.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Index-free adjacency sacrifices the efficiency of queries that do not use graph traversals.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Native graph databases use index-free adjacency to process CRUD operations on the stored data.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Multiple categories of graphs by kind of data have been recognised.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Codd's 1970 paper on the relational model, relational databases have been the de facto industry standard for large-scale data storage systems.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Relational models require a strict schema and data normalization which separates data into many tables and removes any duplicate data within the database.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Data is normalized in order to preserve data consistency and support ACID transactions.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] However this imposes limitations on how relationships can be queried.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] One of the relational model's design motivations was to achieve a fast row-by-row access.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Problems arise when there is a need to form complex relationships between the stored data.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Although relationships can be analyzed with the relational model, complex queries performing many join operations on many different attributes over several tables are required.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In working with relational models, foreign key constraints should also be considered when retrieving relationships, causing additional overhead.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Compared with relational databases, graph databases are often faster for associative data sets and map more directly to the structure of object-oriented applications.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] They can scale more naturally to large datasets as they do not typically need join operations, which can often be expensive.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] As they depend less on a rigid schema, they are marketed as more suitable to manage ad hoc and changing data with evolving schemas.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Conversely, relational database management systems are typically faster at performing the same operation on large numbers of data elements, permitting the manipulation of the data in its natural structure.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Despite the graph databases' advantages and recent popularity over relational databases, it is recommended the graph model itself should not be the sole reason to replace an existing relational database.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] A graph database may become relevant if there is an evidence for performance improvement by orders of magnitude and lower latency.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] The relational model gathers data together using information in the data.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] For example, one might look for all the "users" whose phone number contains the area code "311".
[src:arangodb/graph-database] This would be done by searching selected datastores, or tables, looking in the selected phone number fields for the string "311".
[src:arangodb/graph-database] This can be a time-consuming process in large tables, so relational databases offer indexes, which allow data to be stored in a smaller sub-table, containing only the selected data and a unique key (or primary key) of the record.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] If the phone numbers are indexed, the same search would occur in the smaller index table, gathering the keys of matching records, and then looking in the main data table for the records with those keys.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Usually, a table is stored in a way that allows a lookup via a key to be very fast.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Relational databases do not *inherently* contain the idea of fixed relationships between records.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Instead, related data is linked to each other by storing one record's unique key in another record's data.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] For example, a table containing email addresses for users might hold a data item called `userpk`, which contains the primary key of the user record it is associated with.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] This operation, termed a join, can be computationally expensive.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Depending on the complexity of the query, the number of joins, and indexing various keys, the system may have to search through multiple tables and indexes and then sort it all to match it together.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In contrast, graph databases directly store the relationships between records.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Instead of an email address being found by looking up its user's key in the `userpk` column, the user record contains a pointer that directly refers to the email address record.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] That is, having selected a user, the pointer can be followed directly to the email records, there is no need to search the email table to find the matching records.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] This can eliminate the costly join operations.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] For example, if one searches for all of the email addresses for users in area code "311", the engine would first perform a conventional search to find the users in "311", but then retrieve the email addresses by following the links found in those records.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] A relational database would first find all the users in "311", extract a list of the primary keys, perform another search for any records in the email table with those primary keys, and link the matching records together.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] For these types of common operations, graph databases would theoretically be faster.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] The true value of the graph approach becomes evident when one performs searches that are more than one level deep.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] For example, consider a search for users who have "subscribers" (a table linking users to other users) in the "311" area code.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In this case a relational database has to first search for all the users with an area code in "311", then search the subscribers table for any of those users, and then finally search the users table to retrieve the matching users.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In contrast, a graph database would search for all the users in "311", then follow the backlinks through the subscriber relationship to find the subscriber users.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] This avoids several searches, look-ups, and the memory usage involved in holding all of the temporary data from multiple records needed to construct the output.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In terms of big O notation, this query would be $O(\log n)+O(1)$ time – i.e., proportional to the logarithm of the size of the data.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In contrast, the relational version would be multiple $O(\log n)$ lookups, plus the $O(n)$ time needed to join all of the data records.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] The relative advantage of graph retrieval grows with the complexity of a query.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] For example, one might want to know "that movie about submarines with the actor who was in that movie with that other actor that played the lead in *Gone With the Wind*".
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In a relational database, this would require several separate searches through the movies and actors tables, doing another search on submarine movies, finding all the actors in those movies, and then comparing the (large) collected results.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In contrast, the graph database would walk from *Gone With the Wind* to Clark Gable, gather the links to the movies he has been in, gather the links out of those movies to other actors, and then follow the links out of those actors back to the list of movies.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] The resulting list of movies can then be searched for "submarine".
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Relational databases are very well suited to flat data layouts, where relationships between data are only one or two levels deep.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] For example, an accounting database might need to look up all the line items for all the invoices for a given customer, a three-join query.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] Graph databases are aimed at datasets that contain many more links.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] They are especially well suited to social networking systems, where the "friends" relationship is essentially unbounded.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] These properties make graph databases naturally suited to types of searches that are increasingly common in online systems, and in big data environments.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] For this reason, graph databases are becoming very popular for large online systems like Facebook, Google, Twitter, and similar systems with deep links between records.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] To further illustrate, imagine a relational model with two tables: a `people` table (which has a `person_id` and `person_name` column) and a `friend` table (with `friend_id` and `person_id`, which is a foreign key from the `people` table).
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In this case, searching for all of Jack's friends would result in the following SQL query.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] The above examples are a simple illustration of a basic relationship query.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] They condense the idea of relational models' query complexity that increases with the total amount of data.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] In comparison, a graph database query is easily able to sort through the relationship graph to present the results.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] There are also results that indicate simple, condensed, and declarative queries of the graph databases do not necessarily provide good performance in comparison to the relational databases.
[src:arangodb/graph-database] While graph databases offer an intuitive representation of data, relational databases offer better results when set operations are needed.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] In the field of database design, a **multi-model database** is a database management system designed to support multiple data models against a single, integrated backend.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] In contrast, most database management systems are organized around a single data model that determines how data can be organized, stored, and manipulated.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] Document, graph, relational, and key–value models are examples of data models that may be supported by a multi-model database.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] The relational data model became popular after its publication by Edgar F.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] Due to increasing requirements for horizontal scalability and fault tolerance, NoSQL databases became prominent after 2009.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] NoSQL databases use a variety of data models, with document, graph, and key–value models being popular.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] A multi-model database is a database that can store, index and query data in more than one model.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] For some time, databases have primarily supported only one model, such as: relational database, document-oriented database, graph database or triplestore.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] A database that combines many of these is multi-model.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] This should not be confused with multimodal database systems such as Pixeltable or ApertureDB, which focus on unified management of different media types (images, video, audio, text) rather than different data models.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] For some time, it was all but forgotten (or considered irrelevant) that there were any other database models besides relational.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] The relational model and notion of third normal form were the default standard for all data storage.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] However, prior to the dominance of relational data modeling, from about 1980 to 2005, the hierarchical database model was commonly used.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] Since 2000 or 2010, many NoSQL models that are non-relational, including documents, triples, key–value stores and graphs are popular.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] Arguably, geospatial data, temporal data, and text data are also separate models, though indexed, queryable text data is generally termed a "search engine" rather than a database.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] The first time the word "multi-model" has been associated to the databases was on May 30, 2012 in Cologne, Germany, during the Luca Garulli's key note "*NoSQL Adoption – What’s the Next Step?*".
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] Luca Garulli envisioned the evolution of the 1st generation NoSQL products into new products with more features able to be used by multiple use cases.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] The idea of multi-model databases can be traced back to Object–Relational Data Management Systems (ORDBMS) in the early 1990s and in a more broader scope even to federated and integrated DBMSs in the early 1980s.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] An ORDBMS system manages different types of data such as relational, object, text and spatial by plugging domain specific data types, functions and index implementations into the DBMS kernels.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] A multi-model database is most directly a response to the "polyglot persistence" approach of knitting together multiple database products, each handing a different model, to achieve a multi-model capability as described by Martin Fowler.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] This strategy has two major disadvantages: it leads to a significant increase in operational complexity, and there is no support for maintaining data consistency across the separate data stores, so multi-model databases have begun to fill in this gap.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] Multi-model databases are intended to offer the data modeling advantages of polyglot persistence, without its disadvantages.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] Operational complexity, in particular, is reduced through the use of a single data store.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] As more and more platforms are proposed to deal with multi-model data, there are a few works on benchmarking multi-model databases.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] For instance, Pluciennik, Oliveira, and UniBench reviewed existing multi-model databases and made an evaluation effort towards comparing multi-model databases and other SQL and NoSQL databases respectively.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] 2. they can employ a unified query language such as AQL, Orient SQL, SQL/XML, SQL/JSON to retrieve correlated multi-model data, such as graph-JSON-key/value, XML-relational, and JSON-relational in a single platform.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] 3. they are able to support multi-model ACID transactions in the stand-alone mode.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] The main difference between the available multi-model databases is related to their architectures.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] Multi-model databases can support different models either within the engine or via different layers on top of the engine.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] Some products may provide an engine which supports documents and graphs while others provide layers on top of a key-key store.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] With a layered architecture, each data model is provided via its own component.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] In addition to offering multiple data models in a single data store, some databases allow developers to easily define custom data models.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] This capability is enabled by ACID transactions with high performance and scalability.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] In order for a custom data model to support concurrent updates, the database must be able to synchronize updates across multiple keys.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] ACID transactions, if they are sufficiently performant, allow such synchronization.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] JSON documents, graphs, and relational tables can all be implemented in a manner that inherits the horizontal scalability and fault-tolerance of the underlying data store.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] The traditional theory of relations is not enough to accurately describe multi-model database systems.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] Recent research is focused on developing a new theoretical foundation for these systems.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] Category theory can provide a unified, rigorous language for modeling, integrating, and transforming different data models.
[src:arangodb/multi-model-database] By representing multi-model data as sets and their relationships as functions or relations within the Set category, we can create a formal framework to describe, manipulate, and understand various data models and how they interact.
[src:arangodb/page] ArangoDB combines the analytical power of native graphs with an integrated search engine, JSON support, vector indexes, and a variety of data access patterns via a single, composable query language.
[src:arangodb/page] ArangoDB is available in a community and a commercial edition.
[src:arangodb/page] You can use it for on-premises deployments, self-managed cloud deployments, as well as a fully managed cloud service, the Arango Managed Platform (AMP).
[src:arangodb/page] Graphs are information networks composed of nodes and edges.
[src:arangodb/page] A social network is a common example of a graph.
[src:arangodb/page] People are represented by nodes and their friendships by relations.
[src:arangodb/page] Nodes are also called vertices (singular: vertex), and edges are relations that connect nodes.
[src:arangodb/page] A node typically represents a specific entity (a person, a book, a sensor reading, etc.) and an edge defines how one entity relates to another.
[src:arangodb/page] This paradigm of storing data feels natural because it closely matches the cognitive model of humans.
[src:arangodb/page] It is an expressive data model that allows you to represent many problem domains and solve them with semantic queries and graph analytics.
[src:arangodb/page] ArangoDB lets you equally work with structured, semi-structured, and unstructured data in the form of schema-free JSON objects, without having to connect these objects to form a graph.
[src:arangodb/page] Depending on your needs, you may mix graphs and unconnected data.
[src:arangodb/page] ArangoDB is designed from the ground up to support multiple data models with a single, composable query language.
[src:arangodb/page] ArangoDB also comes with an integrated search engine for information retrieval, such as full-text search with relevance ranking.
[src:arangodb/page] ArangoDB is written in C++ for high performance and built to work at scale, in the cloud or on-premises.
